    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13059_014_0550_8__task_001/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We present DESeq2, a method for differential analysis of count data, using shrinkage estimation for dispersions and fold changes to improve stability and interpretability of estimates.",
      "asbval:note": "DESeq2 is the primary tool presented in the paper; confirmed in abstract and throughout.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "DESeq2",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.057583+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13059_014_0550_8__task_001/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The most common approach in the comparative analysis of transcriptomics data is to test the null hypothesis that the logarithmic fold change (LFC) between treatment and control for a gene's expression is exactly zero... Ranking by fold change, on the other hand, is complicated by the noisiness of LFC estimates for genes with low counts.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper discusses treatment-vs-control comparisons and adjusted p-value thresholds (e.g., 0.1 for FDR), but does not specifically analyze an 'airway dataset'. The paper uses Bottomly et al. and Pickrell et al. datasets for benchmarking, not an airway dataset. The methodology is sound but the specific dataset reference is not found in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How many genes in the airway dataset show statistically significant differential expression (adjusted p-value < 0.1) between treated and untreated conditions when analyzed with DESeq2 using the default FDR threshold?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.057583+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13059_014_0550_8__task_001/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The GLM fit returns coefficients indicating the overall expression strength of the gene and the log2 fold change between treatment and control... DESeq2 reports the standard error for each shrunken LFC estimate... The Wald test P values from the subset of genes that pass an independent filtering step... are adjusted for multiple testing using the procedure of Benjamini and Hochberg.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes log2FoldChange, standard errors (lfcSE), p-values, and adjusted p-values (padj). However, the specific column name 'baseMean' and the exact table structure are not explicitly detailed in the passages provided. The paper discusses these outputs conceptually but does not show the exact output table format with these specific column names.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Results table with columns: baseMean, log2FoldChange, lfcSE, stat, pvalue, padj for treated-vs-untreated contrast",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.057583+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13059_014_0550_8__task_001/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In Figures 2A,B and 3, genes found in this way to be significant at an estimated FDR of 10% are depicted in red... The sensitivity was calculated as the fraction of genes with adjusted P value < 0.1 among the genes with true differences between group means.",
      "asbval:note": "DESeq2 explicitly uses adjusted p-value < 0.1 as a threshold for calling significant genes in multiple benchmarking analyses.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Count of genes with adjusted p-value < 0.1",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.057583+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13059_014_0550_8__task_001/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "DESeq2 by default will choose a threshold that maximizes the number of genes found at a user-specified target FDR.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms DESeq2 uses FDR-based thresholding; 0.1 (10%) is used as the target FDR in benchmarks.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "default FDR threshold",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.057583+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13059_014_0550_8__task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The candidate card references an 'airway dataset' which is not mentioned anywhere in the provided paper passages. The paper uses Bottomly et al. (mouse strains) and Pickrell et al. (human lymphoblastoid cell lines) datasets for benchmarking. The airway dataset may be a real dataset used in DESeq2 vignettes or tutorials, but it is not discussed in this paper.",
        "The card appears to be asking for a specific reproducible analysis task (reproduce results on airway dataset), but the paper is a methodological paper describing DESeq2 development and benchmarking, not a case study on the airway dataset."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 2,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.057583+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13059_014_0550_8__task_002/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We present DESeq2, a method for differential analysis of count data, using shrinkage estimation for dispersions and fold changes to improve stability and interpretability of estimates.",
      "asbval:note": "DESeq2 is the primary tool described throughout the paper for differential expression analysis of RNA-seq data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
