      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We present DESeq2, a method for differential analysis of count data, using shrinkage estimation for dispersions and fold changes to improve stability and interpretability of estimates... Accurate estimation of the dispersion parameter \u03b1 i is critical for the statistical inference of differential expression.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes dispersion estimation as a core component of DESeq2 for RNA-seq count data analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Estimate gene-wise dispersion parameters for negative binomial generalized linear models in RNA-seq count data using DESeq2. This is a foundational step in differential expression analysis that accounts for the mean-variance relationship inherent in RNA-seq data.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:03.457424+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In DESeq2, we assume that genes of similar average expression strength have similar dispersion... We first treat each gene separately and estimate gene-wise dispersion estimates (using maximum likelihood)... we fit a smooth curve... We then shrink the gene-wise dispersion estimates toward the values predicted by the curve to obtain final dispersion values... We use an empirical Bayes approach (Methods), which lets the strength of shrinkage depend (i) on an estimate of how close true dispersion values tend to be to the fit and (ii) on the degrees of freedom.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes the exact methodology claimed: maximum-likelihood estimation followed by empirical Bayes shrinkage toward a fitted trend.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "DESeq2 - Core package that implements dispersion estimation via moderated maximum-likelihood and empirical Bayes shrinkage toward a fitted trend",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:03.457424+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "edgeR [2,3] moderates the dispersion estimate for each gene toward a common estimate across all genes, or toward a local estimate from genes with similar expression strength, using a weighted conditional likelihood... The approach of DESeq2 differs from that of edgeR [3], as DESeq2 estimates the width of the prior distribution from the data and therefore automatically controls the amount of shrinkage based on the observed properties of the data. In contrast, the default steps in edgeR require a user-adjustable parameter, the prior degrees of freedom.",
      "asbval:note": "edgeR IS discussed in the paper as a competitor method for dispersion estimation, contrary to the card's claim that it is 'not discussed in this article.' The paper compares DESeq2's approach to edgeR's approach in detail.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "edgeR - Alternative package for negative binomial dispersion estimation (not discussed in this article but a common competitor)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:03.457424+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The starting point of a DESeq2 analysis is a count matrix K with one row for each gene i and one column for each sample j. The matrix entries K ij indicate the number of sequencing reads that have been unambiguously mapped to a gene in a sample... We model read counts K ij as following a negative binomial distribution... Other methods to obtain count matrices include the htseq-count script [62] and the Bioconductor packages easyRNASeq [63] and featureCount [64].",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes the input format and mentions htseq-count and featureCounts explicitly. Salmon is not mentioned but the general principle of count matrices from quantification tools is supported.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have raw RNA-seq count data (from HTSeq, featureCounts, Salmon, or similar quantification tools) organized in a count matrix with samples as columns and genes as rows, and you need to test for differential expression between conditions using a negative binomial model.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:03.457424+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Accurate estimation of the dispersion parameter \u03b1 i is critical for the statistical inference of differential expression.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper emphasizes the criticality of dispersion estimation for downstream inference.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Dispersion estimation is mandatory before statistical inference on fold changes or p-values.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:03.457424+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "a core challenge is the small number of samples in typical HTS experiments \u2013 often as few as two or three replicates per condition. Inferential methods that treat each gene separately suffer here from lack of power, due to the high uncertainty of within-group variance estimates. In high-throughput assays, this limitation can be overcome by pooling information across genes, specifically, by exploiting assumptions about the similarity of the variances of different genes measured in the same experiment.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper discusses the challenge of small sample sizes and the need for information sharing, supporting the claim about minimum replicate requirements.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have fewer than ~3 biological replicates per condition; dispersion sharing across genes relies on sufficient sample size to fit a robust trend.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:03.457424+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The starting point of a DESeq2 analysis is a count matrix K with one row for each gene i and one column for each sample j. The matrix entries K ij indicate the number of sequencing reads that have been unambiguously mapped to a gene in a sample.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper specifies that DESeq2 works with raw read counts, not normalized values.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "dispersion-estimation-negative-binomial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Your data are already normalized (e.g., log2-transformed, FPKM, or TPM values); DESeq2 requires raw integer counts.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:03.457424+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/factor-design-specification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In linear modeling, a categorical variable or factor can take on two or more values or levels... The use of linear models, however, provides the flexibility to also analyze more complex designs, as is often useful in genomic studies",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly discusses design matrices, factors, and complex experimental designs in the context of GLM fitting for differential expression.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "factor-design-specification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Define and encode the experimental design formula in DESeq2 that specifies which variables (factors) explain variation in RNA-seq counts, including covariates (batch effects, treatment groups) and their interactions.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:18.926216+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/factor-design-specification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In the simplest case of a comparison between two groups, such as treated and control samples, the design matrix elements indicate whether a sample j is treated or not, and the GLM fit returns coefficients indicating the overall expression strength of the gene and the log2 fold change between treatment and control.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates that design matrix structure directly determines which coefficients are estimated and their interpretation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "factor-design-specification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Proper design specification is foundational to accurate differential expression analysis, as it determines which coefficients are estimated and tested.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:18.926216+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/factor-design-specification/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We use GLMs with a logarithmic link, log2 qij = \u03a3r xjr \u03b2ir, with design matrix elements xjr and coefficients \u03b2ir... The use of linear models, however, provides the flexibility to also analyze more complex designs, as is often useful in genomic studies",
      "asbval:note": "DESeq2 is the primary tool discussed; paper explicitly describes how design matrices are used in GLM fitting.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "factor-design-specification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "DESeq2 accepts design formula and constructs/fits the negative binomial GLM; design determines which coefficients are estimated and tested",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:18.926216+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
