      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fold-change-interpretation-and-ranking/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "DESeq2 reports the standard error for each shrunken LFC estimate... For significance testing, DESeq2 uses a Wald test: the shrunken estimate of LFC is divided by its standard error, resulting in a z-statistic, which is compared to a standard normal distribution... The Wald test P values from the subset of genes that pass an independent filtering step, described in the next section, are adjusted for multiple testing using the procedure of Benjamini and Hochberg [21].",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes the output structure: shrunken LFC estimates, standard errors, p-values, and adjusted p-values (via Benjamini-Hochberg).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fold-change-interpretation-and-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "After running DESeq() on a DESeqDataSet and extracting results with results(dds), you have a results table with log\u2082 fold changes, p-values, and adjusted p-values (padj).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:30.166675+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fold-change-interpretation-and-ranking/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In Figures 2A,B and 3, genes found in this way to be significant at an estimated FDR of 10% are depicted in red.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly uses padj < 0.1 (FDR = 10%) as a significance threshold in examples.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fold-change-interpretation-and-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "identify genes meeting a significance threshold (e.g., padj < 0.1 for FDR control)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:30.166675+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fold-change-interpretation-and-ranking/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Ranking by fold change, on the other hand, is complicated by the noisiness of LFC estimates for genes with low counts... This makes shrunken LFCs also suitable for ranking genes, e.g., to prioritize them for follow-up experiments.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly discusses ranking genes by fold change magnitude and prioritizing for follow-up validation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fold-change-interpretation-and-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "rank them by magnitude of effect to prioritize strong signals",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:30.166675+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fold-change-interpretation-and-ranking/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The shrunken MAP LFCs offer a more reproducible quantification of transcriptional differences than standard MLE LFCs... This makes shrunken fold-change estimates offer a more reliable basis for quantitative conclusions than normal MLEs. This makes shrunken LFCs also suitable for ranking genes, e.g., to prioritize them for follow-up experiments.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes shrunken LFCs as suitable for ranking and prioritization for downstream validation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fold-change-interpretation-and-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "create a filtered, ordered list for publication or functional validation",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:30.166675+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "IHW is not mentioned anywhere in the DESeq2 paper passages. The paper discusses independent filtering (passage [7], [18]) as a method to improve power by filtering genes with low mean normalized counts before multiple testing adjustment, but does not describe or reference IHW as a weighting-based method. The paper's independent filtering is a binary filter, not a weighting scheme.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Independent Hypothesis Weighting (IHW) is a data-driven filtering and multiple-testing correction method that weights p-values according to informative covariates (such as mean normalized counts) to increase statistical power while controlling false discovery rate.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:45.956999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The DESeq2 paper does not describe IHW or any adaptive \u03b1-allocation weighting method. The paper's independent filtering approach (passages [7], [18]) removes low-power genes before multiple testing adjustment but does not adaptively weight p-values by covariate.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "IHW is applied after differential expression testing to improve gene discovery by adaptively allocating \u03b1-level to genes where statistical power is highest.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:45.956999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We present DESeq2, a method for differential analysis of count data, using shrinkage estimation for dispersions and fold changes to improve stability and interpretability of estimates... For significance testing, DESeq2 uses a Wald test: the shrunken estimate of LFC is divided by its standard error, resulting in a z-statistic, which is compared to a standard normal distribution.",
      "asbval:note": "DESeq2 does perform GLM fitting and generates p-values via Wald test (passage [7]). However, the claim that it is a 'required upstream step before IHW filtering' cannot be verified because IHW is not discussed in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "DESeq2 performs negative binomial GLM fitting and generates raw p-values and test statistics; required upstream step before IHW filtering",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:45.956999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "IHW is not mentioned in the DESeq2 paper. The paper does not describe integration of IHW into DESeq2's results() function or any filterFun parameter for weighting. The paper discusses independent filtering via mean normalized counts (passage [7], [18]) but this is a binary filter, not a weighting method.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "IHW (Independent Hypothesis Weighting) is a core method integrated into DESeq2's results() function via filterFun parameter; adaptively weights hypotheses by informative covariate to improve power",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:45.956999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "ashr is not mentioned in the DESeq2 paper. The paper does discuss shrinkage of LFCs (passages [4], [6]) but does not reference ashr or an lfcShrink() function. The shrinkage is performed directly within DESeq2's empirical Bayes framework, not via a separate ashr package.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ashr is a related adaptive shrinkage method for effect size estimation; complements IHW by providing shrunk log fold changes via lfcShrink()",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:45.956999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "This evidence span is not found in any of the provided passages. The paper does not mention IHW or a Bioconductor package for IHW. The only Bioconductor package mentioned is DESeq2 itself (passage [2], [4]).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[evidence_spans]",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "A Bioconductor package, [IHW](http://bioconductor.org/packages/IHW), is available that implements the method of *Independent Hypothesis Weighting*",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:45.956999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "IHW is not discussed in the DESeq2 paper. The paper does describe independent filtering as a built-in feature of DESeq2 (passages [7], [18]) that improves power, but does not mention IHW as an alternative or complementary method.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "hypothesis-weighting-statistical-control",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have completed DESeq2 differential expression analysis on RNA-seq count data and obtained p-values for each gene, use IHW if you want to improve power to detect true positives beyond standard independent filtering.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:45.956999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Due to the large number of tests performed in the analysis of RNA-seq and other genome-wide experiments, the multiple testing problem needs to be addressed... DESeq2 uses the average expression strength of each gene, across all samples, as its filter criterion, and it omits all genes with mean normalized counts below a filtering threshold from multiple testing adjustment. DESeq2 by default will choose a threshold that maximizes the number of genes found at a user-specified target FDR.",
      "asbval:note": "Claim is directly supported by passage describing independent filtering and FDR control.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Automatically filter low-abundance genes before multiple-testing correction in RNA-seq differential expression analysis to improve statistical power and control false discovery rate.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:59.240051+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "DESeq2 uses the average expression strength of each gene, across all samples, as its filter criterion, and it omits all genes with mean normalized counts below a filtering threshold from multiple testing adjustment... The Wald test P values from the subset of genes that pass an independent filtering step... are adjusted for multiple testing using the procedure of Benjamini and Hochberg.",
      "asbval:note": "Both independent filtering and Benjamini-Hochberg FDR correction are explicitly described as integrated steps.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill combines independent filtering (removing genes with low mean normalized counts) with FDR-based multiple-testing correction",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:59.240051+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We present DESeq2, a method for differential analysis of count data, using shrinkage estimation for dispersions and fold changes... The DESeq2 package is available at http://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/html/DESeq2.html... A single function, called DESeq, is used to run the default analysis, while lower-level functions are also available for advanced users.",
      "asbval:note": "DESeq2 is confirmed as the primary tool. Paper mentions a 'DESeq' function for default analysis and lower-level functions; no explicit mention of 'results()' function by name, but the functionality is described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "DESeq2 - Performs negative binomial GLM fitting, independent filtering, and multiple-testing correction via results() function",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:59.240051+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "ashr is not mentioned anywhere in the paper passages. The paper discusses shrinkage estimation extensively but does not reference the ashr package.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ashr - Provides adaptive shrinkage methods for improved effect size estimation that can follow independent filtering and FDR correction",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:59.240051+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/independent-filtering-multiple-testing-correction/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "DEvis is not mentioned in any of the paper passages. The paper does not discuss this visualization tool.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
