    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "DESeq2 integrates methodological advances with several novel features to facilitate a more quantitative analysis of comparative RNA-seq data using shrinkage estimators for dispersion and fold change... Empirical Bayes shrinkage for fold-change estimation... DESeq2 overcomes this issue by shrinking LFC estimates toward zero in a manner such that shrinkage is stronger when the available information for a gene is low",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes empirical Bayes shrinkage of LFC estimates as a core feature of DESeq2, but does NOT mention lfcShrink() function or specific estimator types (apeglm, normal, ashr). The paper describes the shrinkage methodology itself but not the named function or these specific estimator options. The lfcShrink() function with these estimator types appears to be a later addition to DESeq2 not covered in this 2014 paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply empirical Bayes shrinkage to log fold change estimates from RNA-seq differential expression analysis using DESeq2's lfcShrink() function with multiple estimator types (apeglm, normal, ashr)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:21:21.623506+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "DESeq2 overcomes this issue by shrinking LFC estimates toward zero in a manner such that shrinkage is stronger when the available information for a gene is low, which may be because counts are low, dispersion is high or there are few degrees of freedom... The resulting MAP LFCs are biased toward zero in a manner that removes the problem of exaggerated LFCs for low counts... The shrinkage of LFC estimates can be described as a bias-variance trade-off: for genes with little information for LFC estimation, a reduction of the strong variance is bought at the cost of accepting a bias toward zero, and this can result in an overall reduction in mean squared error",
      "asbval:note": "Directly supported: paper explicitly describes shrinkage reducing variance for low-count and high-dispersion genes, and improving stability/interpretability.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Shrinkage reduces noise in fold change estimates, particularly for genes with high dispersion or low counts, improving interpretability and reducing false positives",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:21:21.623506+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We present DESeq2, a method for differential analysis of count data, using shrinkage estimation for dispersions and fold changes... The DESeq2 package is available at http://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/html/DESeq2.html... DESeq2 is implemented as a package for the R statistical environment and is available as part of the Bioconductor project",
      "asbval:note": "DESeq2 is confirmed as the core package with DESeq() and results() functions. The paper describes shrinkage of fold changes as a core feature. However, the paper does NOT mention lfcShrink() function by name\u2014this appears to be a later addition. The GitHub repo URL cannot be verified from the paper. The paper confirms DESeqDataSet class and dispersion/fold-change shrinkage methodology but not the specific lfcShrink() function interface.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "DESeq2 with repo https://github.com/thelovelab/DESeq2 and role: Core package providing DESeqDataSet class, DESeq() normalization/dispersion estimation, results() extraction, and lfcShrink() function for shrinkage",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:21:21.623506+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The paper does not mention ashr, lfcShrink(), or the 'ashr' estimator type. The paper describes DESeq2's own empirical Bayes shrinkage approach using a zero-centered normal prior, not a mixture-of-normals approach. ashr is not discussed in any of the provided passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ashr with repo https://github.com/stephens999/ashr and role: Provides adaptive shrinkage estimator (type='ashr' option in lfcShrink()); implements mixture-of-normals shrinkage with adaptive prior learning from data",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:21:21.623506+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The paper does not mention the 'airway' dataset. The paper uses Bottomly et al. and Pickrell et al. datasets for demonstrations, not airway. The airway dataset is not referenced in any passage.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "airway as example SummarizedExperiment dataset used to demonstrate lfcShrink() workflow on treated-vs-untreated contrast",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:21:21.623506+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The starting point of a DESeq2 analysis is a count matrix K... For each gene, we fit a generalized linear model (GLM)... Empirical Bayes shrinkage for fold-change estimation... We demonstrate the advantages of DESeq2's new features by describing a number of applications possible with shrunken fold changes and their estimates of standard error",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes the workflow of fitting models and then applying shrinkage to fold changes, consistent with the scope description.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "After running DESeq() and extracting base results with results(), apply shrinkage when you have differential expression estimates and want to reduce the variance of log fold change estimates",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:21:21.623506+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A common difficulty in the analysis of HTS data is the strong variance of LFC estimates for genes with low read count... DESeq2 overcomes this issue by shrinking LFC estimates toward zero in a manner such that shrinkage is stronger when the available information for a gene is low, which may be because counts are low, dispersion is high or there are few degrees of freedom... One sensible solution is to share information across genes",
      "asbval:note": "Directly supported: paper explicitly describes the problem of unreliable estimates for low-count genes and the solution of borrowing strength across genes.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This is especially important for RNA-seq count data where estimates for lowly-expressed genes or genes with high biological variability are unreliable without borrowing strength across the genome",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:21:21.623506+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The Wald test P values from the subset of genes that pass an independent filtering step... are adjusted for multiple testing using the procedure of Benjamini and Hochberg. After GLMs are fit for each gene, one may test whether each model coefficient differs significantly from zero. DESeq2 reports the standard error for each shrunken LFC estimate",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes both shrunken and unshrunken (MLE) estimates being available; benchmarking section compares shrunken vs. unshrunken approaches, supporting the notion that users may need unshrunk estimates for certain purposes.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "log-fold-change-shrinkage-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You require unshrunk log fold changes for variance component estimation or method benchmarking; use the base results() output instead",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:21:21.623506+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/ma-plot-visualization-and-interpretation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Plots of the (A) MLE (i.e., no shrinkage) and (B) MAP estimate (i.e., with shrinkage) for the LFCs attributable to mouse strain, over the average expression strength for a ten vs eleven sample comparison",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly uses MA-plots (mean vs. log fold change) to visualize differential expression across expression strength range.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "ma-plot-visualization-and-interpretation",
