    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/results-table-extraction-and-comparison/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We demonstrate the advantages of DESeq2's new features by describing a number of applications possible with shrunken fold changes and their estimates of standard error, including improved gene ranking and visualization, hypothesis tests above and below a threshold, and the regularized logarithm transformation for quality assessment and clustering of overdispersed count data.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper discusses MA-plots and visualization of results (e.g., Figure 2A, 2B show MA-plots of fold changes), but does not specifically mention ggplot2 or volcano plots. Visualization is discussed generically; specific tools are not named.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "results-table-extraction-and-comparison",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ggplot2 / base R graphics - Visualization of results-table comparisons via MA-plots, volcano plots, and summary statistics across estimators",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:22:10.912211+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/results-table-extraction-and-comparison/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The starting point of a DESeq2 analysis is a count matrix K... For each gene, we fit a generalized linear model (GLM)... The use of linear models, however, provides the flexibility to also analyze more complex designs, as is often useful in genomic studies.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes DESeq2 workflow and contrasts, but does not mention results() function or the ability to apply multiple shrinkage estimators post-hoc via lfcShrink(). The paper describes the built-in shrinkage approach, not a workflow for comparing multiple estimators on the same results object.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "results-table-extraction-and-comparison",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "After running DESeq() on a DESeqDataSet and obtaining initial results via results(), use this skill when you need to (1) extract base results tables for specific contrasts (e.g., treated vs. untreated), (2) apply multiple shrinkage estimators to the same results object to compare",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:22:10.912211+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
