    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/rna-seq-differential-expression-analysis/012",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The starting point of a DESeq2 analysis is a count matrix K with one row for each gene i and one column for each sample j. The matrix entries K ij indicate the number of sequencing reads that have been unambiguously mapped to a gene in a sample.",
      "asbval:note": "The scope description accurately reflects DESeq2's input requirements as described in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "rna-seq-differential-expression-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have RNA-seq read count data (from alignment tools, transcript quantification, or feature counting) organized in a count matrix with samples as columns and genes as rows, paired with sample metadata (condition, batch, treatment)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:22:29.710269+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/rna-seq-differential-expression-analysis/013",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Note that although we refer in this paper to counts of reads in genes, the methods presented here can be applied as well to other kinds of HTS count data... The starting point of a DESeq2 analysis is a count matrix K with one row for each gene i and one column for each sample j. The matrix entries K ij indicate the number of sequencing reads...",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms DESeq2 works with raw counts and performs normalization internally.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "rna-seq-differential-expression-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input data is already normalized or log-transformed (DESeq2 expects raw integer counts and performs its own normalization).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:22:29.710269+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/rna-seq-experimental-design-specification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In linear modeling, a categorical variable or factor can take on two or more values or levels. In standard design matrices, one of the values is chosen as a reference value or base level and absorbed into the intercept... the design matrix elements indicate whether a sample j is treated or not, and the GLM fit returns coefficients indicating the overall expression strength of the gene and the log 2 fold change between treatment and control. The use of linear models, however, provides the flexibility to also analyze more complex designs, as is often useful in genomic studies.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly describes design matrices and their role in specifying biological contrasts and statistical models for differential expression testing.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "rna-seq-experimental-design-specification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Define sample metadata, condition labels, and design formulas that specify the biological contrasts and statistical model for differential expression testing in DESeq2.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:22:46.019416+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/rna-seq-experimental-design-specification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The starting point of a DESeq2 analysis is a count matrix K with one row for each gene i and one column for each sample j... We model read counts K ij as following a negative binomial distribution... We use GLMs with a logarithmic link, log 2 q ij = (cid:2) r x jr \u03b2 ir , with design matrix elements x jr and coefficients \u03b2 ir.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes DESeq2's use of design matrices and negative binomial GLM fitting.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-014-0550-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
